{
    "level": "sentence",
    "abstract": [
        {
            "text": "We outline the opportunities for spin physics which are offered by a next generation and multi-purpose fixed-target experiment exploiting the proton LHC beam extracted by a bent crystal. ",
            "paragraph_rank": 1,
            "section_rank": 1
        },
        {
            "text": "In particular, we focus on the study of single transverse spin asymetries with the polarisation of the target.",
            "paragraph_rank": 1,
            "section_rank": 1
        }
    ],
    "body_text": [
        {
            "text": "Introduction",
            "section_rank": 2
        },
        {
            "text": "Fixed-target experiments lead to numerous breakthroughs in particle and nuclear physics. ",
            "section": "Introduction",
            "paragraph_rank": 2,
            "section_rank": 2
        },
        {
            "text": "In particular they contributed to the discovery of anomalously large single [1] and double-spin [2] correlations in hadron-hadron collisions.",
            "section": "Introduction",
            "paragraph_rank": 2,
            "section_rank": 2,
            "ref_spans": [
                {
                    "start": 76,
                    "end": 79,
                    "type": "bibr",
                    "ref_id": "b0",
                    "text": "[1]"
                },
                {
                    "start": 96,
                    "end": 99,
                    "type": "bibr",
                    "ref_id": "b1",
                    "text": "[2]"
                }
            ]
        },
        {
            "text": "New opportunities [3,4] are at reach thanks to the LHC beam of 7 TeV protons interacting on a fixed target, be it polarised or unpolarised. ",
            "section": "Introduction",
            "paragraph_rank": 3,
            "section_rank": 2,
            "ref_spans": [
                {
                    "start": 18,
                    "end": 21,
                    "type": "bibr",
                    "ref_id": "b2",
                    "text": "[3,"
                },
                {
                    "start": 21,
                    "end": 23,
                    "type": "bibr",
                    "ref_id": "b3",
                    "text": "4]"
                }
            ]
        },
        {
            "text": "Such opportunities can be studied by a future multi-purpose experiment, thereafter named AFTER for \"A Fixed-Target ExperRiment\". ",
            "section": "Introduction",
            "paragraph_rank": 3,
            "section_rank": 2,
            "entity_spans": [
                {
                    "start": 89,
                    "end": 95,
                    "type": "software",
                    "rawForm": "AFTER",
                    "resp": "service",
                    "id": "software-simple-s1"
                }
            ]
        },
        {
            "text": "The LHC proton beam colliding on fixed targets releases a cms energy close to 115 GeV, i.e. an energy never reached in a fixed-target experiment, between SPS and RHIC.",
            "section": "Introduction",
            "paragraph_rank": 3,
            "section_rank": 2
        },
        {
            "text": "One of the essential advantages of a fixed-target experiment is the possibility to polarize the target (see e.g. [5]) to measure Single Spin Asymmetry (SSA) in a number of hard reactions. ",
            "section": "Introduction",
            "paragraph_rank": 4,
            "section_rank": 2,
            "ref_spans": [
                {
                    "start": 113,
                    "end": 116,
                    "type": "bibr",
                    "ref_id": "b4",
                    "text": "[5]"
                }
            ]
        },
        {
            "text": "We discuss here the opportunities offered by the measurements of such SSAs.",
            "section": "Introduction",
            "paragraph_rank": 4,
            "section_rank": 2
        },
        {
            "text": "Beam extraction and target polarisation",
            "section_rank": 3
        },
        {
            "text": "The extraction of beams by means of bent-crystal chanelling offers an ideal and cost-effective way to obtain a clean and very collimated beam without specific limitation on its energy. ",
            "section": "Beam extraction and target polarisation",
            "paragraph_rank": 5,
            "section_rank": 3
        },
        {
            "text": "This would not alter the LHC beam performance [6,7]. ",
            "section": "Beam extraction and target polarisation",
            "paragraph_rank": 5,
            "section_rank": 3,
            "ref_spans": [
                {
                    "start": 46,
                    "end": 49,
                    "type": "bibr",
                    "ref_id": "b5",
                    "text": "[6,"
                },
                {
                    "start": 49,
                    "end": 51,
                    "type": "bibr",
                    "ref_id": "b6",
                    "text": "7]"
                }
            ]
        },
        {
            "text": "The \"smart collimator\" solution on the 7-TeV LHC beam will be tested by the CERN LUA9 collaboration after the 2013 shutdown [8]. ",
            "section": "Beam extraction and target polarisation",
            "paragraph_rank": 5,
            "section_rank": 3,
            "ref_spans": [
                {
                    "start": 124,
                    "end": 127,
                    "type": "bibr",
                    "ref_id": "b7",
                    "text": "[8]"
                }
            ]
        },
        {
            "text": "Another proposal, which deserves to be further investigated, is to \"replace\" the kicker-modules in LHC section IR6 by a bent crystal [7].",
            "section": "Beam extraction and target polarisation",
            "paragraph_rank": 5,
            "section_rank": 3,
            "ref_spans": [
                {
                    "start": 133,
                    "end": 136,
                    "type": "bibr",
                    "ref_id": "b6",
                    "text": "[7]"
                }
            ]
        },
        {
            "text": "A significant fraction of the beam loss can then been extracted, with an intensity reaching 5 \u00d7 10 8 p + s \u22121 . ",
            "section": "Beam extraction and target polarisation",
            "paragraph_rank": 6,
            "section_rank": 3
        },
        {
            "text": "This corresponds to an average extraction per bunch per revolution of mini-bunches of about 15 p + . ",
            "section": "Beam extraction and target polarisation",
            "paragraph_rank": 6,
            "section_rank": 3
        },
        {
            "text": "With typical targets, the yearly (10 7 s) integrated luminosities are of the order of an inverse fb. ",
            "section": "Beam extraction and target polarisation",
            "paragraph_rank": 6,
            "section_rank": 3
        },
        {
            "text": "For more details, the reader is guided to [3].",
            "section": "Beam extraction and target polarisation",
            "paragraph_rank": 6,
            "section_rank": 3,
            "ref_spans": [
                {
                    "start": 42,
                    "end": 45,
                    "type": "bibr",
                    "ref_id": "b2",
                    "text": "[3]"
                }
            ]
        },
        {
            "text": "Whereas outstanding luminosities can be obtained, the intensity of the extracted beam is not extremely large and does not constrain the choice of the target polarisation technique. ",
            "section": "Beam extraction and target polarisation",
            "paragraph_rank": 7,
            "section_rank": 3
        },
        {
            "text": "Since the beam is highly energetic, one expects a minimum ionisation and a low heating of the target. ",
            "section": "Beam extraction and target polarisation",
            "paragraph_rank": 7,
            "section_rank": 3
        },
        {
            "text": "The heating power due to the AFTER beam would be of the order of 50 \u00b5W for a typical 1 cm thick target. ",
            "section": "Beam extraction and target polarisation",
            "paragraph_rank": 7,
            "section_rank": 3,
            "entity_spans": [
                {
                    "start": 29,
                    "end": 35,
                    "type": "software",
                    "rawForm": "AFTER",
                    "resp": "service",
                    "id": "software-simple-s2"
                }
            ]
        },
        {
            "text": "This allows one to maintain target temperatures as low as 50 mK. ",
            "section": "Beam extraction and target polarisation",
            "paragraph_rank": 7,
            "section_rank": 3
        },
        {
            "text": "Relaxation times can last as long as one month in the spin-frozen mode. ",
            "section": "Beam extraction and target polarisation",
            "paragraph_rank": 7,
            "section_rank": 3
        },
        {
            "text": "As regards the damages on the target, they typically arise after an irradiation of 10 15 p + cm \u22122 [9, 10], i.e. one month of beam in our case.",
            "section": "Beam extraction and target polarisation",
            "paragraph_rank": 7,
            "section_rank": 3
        },
        {
            "text": "Yet, the available space in the underground LHC complex can be a major constraint. ",
            "section": "Beam extraction and target polarisation",
            "paragraph_rank": 8,
            "section_rank": 3
        },
        {
            "text": "This restricts the choice to polarisation by continuous Dynamic Nuclear Polarisation DNP or to a HD target [11]. ",
            "section": "Beam extraction and target polarisation",
            "paragraph_rank": 8,
            "section_rank": 3,
            "ref_spans": [
                {
                    "start": 107,
                    "end": 111,
                    "type": "bibr",
                    "ref_id": "b10",
                    "text": "[11]"
                }
            ]
        },
        {
            "text": "Both take less space than the frozen-spin machinery. ",
            "section": "Beam extraction and target polarisation",
            "paragraph_rank": 8,
            "section_rank": 3
        },
        {
            "text": "CERN has a long tradition of DNP for various materials such as NH 3 , Li 6 D [12]. ",
            "section": "Beam extraction and target polarisation",
            "paragraph_rank": 8,
            "section_rank": 3,
            "ref_spans": [
                {
                    "start": 77,
                    "end": 81,
                    "type": "bibr",
                    "ref_id": "b11",
                    "text": "[12]"
                }
            ]
        },
        {
            "text": "Experts of DNP can still be found worlwide, whereas HD target makers are more rare. ",
            "section": "Beam extraction and target polarisation",
            "paragraph_rank": 8,
            "section_rank": 3
        },
        {
            "text": "One can cite two groups: one at TJNAF (USA) and the other at RCNP (Japan) [13]. ",
            "section": "Beam extraction and target polarisation",
            "paragraph_rank": 8,
            "section_rank": 3,
            "ref_spans": [
                {
                    "start": 74,
                    "end": 78,
                    "type": "bibr",
                    "ref_id": "b12",
                    "text": "[13]"
                }
            ]
        },
        {
            "text": "We are hopeful that AFTER will motivate our colleagues working on DNP to revisit the necessary technology [14].",
            "section": "Beam extraction and target polarisation",
            "paragraph_rank": 8,
            "section_rank": 3,
            "ref_spans": [
                {
                    "start": 106,
                    "end": 110,
                    "type": "bibr",
                    "ref_id": "b13",
                    "text": "[14]"
                }
            ],
            "entity_spans": [
                {
                    "start": 20,
                    "end": 26,
                    "type": "software",
                    "rawForm": "AFTER",
                    "resp": "service",
                    "id": "software-simple-s3"
                }
            ]
        },
        {
            "text": "Physics",
            "section_rank": 4
        },
        {
            "text": "It has recently been re-emphasized that a type of parton distribution functions, the Sivers functions [15], can be accessed in SSAs for hard reactions which involve a transversely polarized proton (see e.g. [16]). ",
            "section": "Physics",
            "paragraph_rank": 9,
            "section_rank": 4,
            "ref_spans": [
                {
                    "start": 102,
                    "end": 106,
                    "type": "bibr",
                    "ref_id": "b14",
                    "text": "[15]"
                },
                {
                    "start": 207,
                    "end": 211,
                    "type": "bibr",
                    "ref_id": "b15",
                    "text": "[16]"
                }
            ]
        },
        {
            "text": "The Sivers functions encode information on the correlation between the proton spin and the momentum inside the proton of a parton in the transverse direction.",
            "section": "Physics",
            "paragraph_rank": 9,
            "section_rank": 4
        },
        {
            "text": "As such they are linked to the orbital motion of partons in the polarised nucleon. ",
            "section": "Physics",
            "paragraph_rank": 10,
            "section_rank": 4
        },
        {
            "text": "Such asymmetries have been observed in hadron-hadron collisions in forward pion [1,17,18] and kaon production [17] at Fermilab and Brookhaven. ",
            "section": "Physics",
            "paragraph_rank": 10,
            "section_rank": 4,
            "ref_spans": [
                {
                    "start": 80,
                    "end": 83,
                    "type": "bibr",
                    "ref_id": "b0",
                    "text": "[1,"
                },
                {
                    "start": 83,
                    "end": 86,
                    "type": "bibr",
                    "ref_id": "b18",
                    "text": "17,"
                },
                {
                    "start": 86,
                    "end": 89,
                    "type": "bibr",
                    "ref_id": "b19",
                    "text": "18]"
                },
                {
                    "start": 110,
                    "end": 114,
                    "type": "bibr",
                    "ref_id": "b18",
                    "text": "[17]"
                }
            ]
        },
        {
            "text": "The high energy of the LHC beam combined with a well designed detector will open a unique access to the large negative-x F domain, essentially unexplored. ",
            "section": "Physics",
            "paragraph_rank": 10,
            "section_rank": 4
        },
        {
            "text": "In this region, the SSA are sensitive to partons with large momentum fractions in the polarised nucleon, x \u2191 . ",
            "section": "Physics",
            "paragraph_rank": 10,
            "section_rank": 4
        },
        {
            "text": "This is where one expects the largest correlation between the motion of the parton and the spin of the nucleon.",
            "section": "Physics",
            "paragraph_rank": 10,
            "section_rank": 4
        },
        {
            "text": "Yet, the Sivers effect for gluons is relatively -if not completely -unknown. ",
            "section": "Physics",
            "paragraph_rank": 11,
            "section_rank": 4
        },
        {
            "text": "This calls for the study of SSAs with gluon sensitive reactions, such as prompt photons, open and closed heavy flavours. ",
            "section": "Physics",
            "paragraph_rank": 11,
            "section_rank": 4
        },
        {
            "text": "Measurements of SSAs in p \u2191 p \u2192 \u03b3X was suggested more than ten years ago in [19] and was shown to be sensitive to the gluon Sivers function [20] for \u221a s of the order of 100 GeV, where the asymmetry may be as large as 10% [21]. ",
            "section": "Physics",
            "paragraph_rank": 11,
            "section_rank": 4,
            "ref_spans": [
                {
                    "start": 76,
                    "end": 80,
                    "type": "bibr",
                    "ref_id": "b20",
                    "text": "[19]"
                },
                {
                    "start": 140,
                    "end": 144,
                    "type": "bibr",
                    "ref_id": "b21",
                    "text": "[20]"
                },
                {
                    "start": 221,
                    "end": 225,
                    "type": "bibr",
                    "ref_id": "b22",
                    "text": "[21]"
                }
            ]
        },
        {
            "text": "Further suggestions to look at gluon-sensitive SSAs were expressed: to look for SSA in photon-jet production [22] with a constraint on the pseudo-rapidities of both the photon and the jet and to look at SSAs in photon-pair production [23].",
            "section": "Physics",
            "paragraph_rank": 11,
            "section_rank": 4,
            "ref_spans": [
                {
                    "start": 109,
                    "end": 113,
                    "type": "bibr",
                    "ref_id": "b23",
                    "text": "[22]"
                },
                {
                    "start": 234,
                    "end": 238,
                    "type": "bibr",
                    "ref_id": "b24",
                    "text": "[23]"
                }
            ]
        },
        {
            "text": "We also guide the reader to two recents publication on spin physics with AFTER, following our first publications on AFTER [3,4]. ",
            "section": "Physics",
            "paragraph_rank": 12,
            "section_rank": 4,
            "ref_spans": [
                {
                    "start": 122,
                    "end": 125,
                    "type": "bibr",
                    "ref_id": "b2",
                    "text": "[3,"
                },
                {
                    "start": 125,
                    "end": 127,
                    "type": "bibr",
                    "ref_id": "b3",
                    "text": "4]"
                }
            ],
            "entity_spans": [
                {
                    "start": 73,
                    "end": 78,
                    "type": "software",
                    "rawForm": "AFTER",
                    "resp": "service",
                    "id": "software-simple-s4"
                },
                {
                    "start": 116,
                    "end": 122,
                    "type": "software",
                    "rawForm": "AFTER",
                    "resp": "service",
                    "id": "software-simple-s5"
                }
            ]
        },
        {
            "text": "The first is about SSA in Drell-Yan reactions [24] as a way to further constrain the quark Sivers effect. ",
            "section": "Physics",
            "paragraph_rank": 12,
            "section_rank": 4,
            "ref_spans": [
                {
                    "start": 46,
                    "end": 50,
                    "type": "bibr",
                    "ref_id": "b25",
                    "text": "[24]"
                }
            ]
        },
        {
            "text": "The second is about the production of spinless quarkonium in unpolarised proton-proton collisions [25] as a way to probe the dynamics of linearly polarized gluons inside unpolarized protons.",
            "section": "Physics",
            "paragraph_rank": 12,
            "section_rank": 4,
            "ref_spans": [
                {
                    "start": 98,
                    "end": 102,
                    "type": "bibr",
                    "ref_id": "b26",
                    "text": "[25]"
                }
            ]
        },
        {
            "text": "Conclusion",
            "section_rank": 5
        },
        {
            "text": "A fixed-target experiment using the multi-TeV proton beam of the LHC extracted by a bent crystal offers outstanding opportunities for spin physics at unprecedented laboratory energies and momentum transfers. ",
            "section": "Conclusion",
            "paragraph_rank": 13,
            "section_rank": 5
        },
        {
            "text": "As we mentioned, the target polarisation at AFTER should not cause any specific difficulties. ",
            "section": "Conclusion",
            "paragraph_rank": 13,
            "section_rank": 5,
            "entity_spans": [
                {
                    "start": 44,
                    "end": 50,
                    "type": "software",
                    "rawForm": "AFTER",
                    "resp": "service",
                    "id": "software-simple-s6"
                }
            ]
        },
        {
            "text": "Thanks to the extremely high luminosity of the fixed target modeabove the inverse femtobarn per year -, single-spin asymetries could then be measured with high accuracy, in particular for gluon sensitive probes. ",
            "section": "Conclusion",
            "paragraph_rank": 13,
            "section_rank": 5
        },
        {
            "text": "This would open the path for systematic studies of the contribution of the gluon motion to the nucleon spin.",
            "section": "Conclusion",
            "paragraph_rank": 13,
            "section_rank": 5
        },
        {
            "text": "Talk at the SPIN 2012 Conference, JINR, Dubna, September 17 -22, 2012.",
            "paragraph_rank": 14,
            "section_rank": 5
        }
    ]
}